Sure, here's a Java program that simulates a game of coin flipping heads or tails, and a batch file to execute it:

JAVA PROGRAM:
```
import java.util.Random;

public class CoinFlip {
   public static void main(String []args) {
      int rounds = 10; // Number of rounds to play
      int heads = 0;
      int tails = 0;
      Random rand = new Random();

      System.out.println("Let's flip a coin!");

      for (int i = 0; i < rounds; i++) {
         int result = rand.nextInt(2);
         if (result == 0) {
            System.out.println("Round " + (i+1) + ": Heads!");
            heads++;
         } else {
            System.out.println("Round " + (i+1) + ": Tails!");
            tails++;
         }
      }

      System.out.println("\nResults: ");
      System.out.println("Heads: " + heads);
      System.out.println("Tails: " + tails);
   }
}
```

BATCH FILE: Create a new file with the extension ".bat" and paste the following code:

```
@echo off
java CoinFlip
pause
```

The batch file executes the Java program by calling the "java" command followed by the file name of the Java program "CoinFlip". The "pause" command added at the end prevents the command prompt from immediately closing after the program has finished running, allowing the user to view the output.
